<TEXT>
former gov toney anaya said saturday 
that his calling thenpresident reagan antihispanic during the 
early 1980s probably triggered a series of federal investigations 
into anayas administration 
the prominent hispanic democrat addressing a workshop at the 
national association for chicano studies annual conference said he 
made the comment on an economic trip to mexico in 1983 or 1984 
anaya new mexicos governor from 1983 to 1986 was investigated 
by the fbi the us attorneys office in albuquerque and the 
internal revenue service no charges were ever filed against him 
he said saturday that he was asked to comment on reagan and his 
policies toward mexico during a news conference that followed his 
meeting with mexicos president during the trip 
i made the unfortunate statement suggesting that ronald reagan 
was probably the most antihispanic and they translated that to 
mean the most antimexican president wed ever had he recalled 
john ehrlichman who was an aide to president nixon and who 
lives in santa fe read of anayas comment while having breakfast 
with former gov jerry apodaca anaya said 
he told jerry apodaca theyre going to get him the feds are 
going to get your friend anaya theyre not going to tolerate 
that anaya said it wasnt days after that the first of many 
federal investigations were kicked off 
there were 13 fbi investigations altogether there were three 
federal grand jury investigations there was one criminal irs 
investigation and two or three instances where we could trace that 
the cia had been used in these investigations anaya said 
anaya said he didnt learn of ehrlichmans comments until 
recently when apodaca also a democrat related them to him 
apodaca said saturday night anaya took ehrlichmans remarks out 
of context 
apodaca said ehrlichman indicated during their conversation that 
he thought anaya made a major mistake in criticizing reagan 
while outside the united states ehrlichman also said the reagan 
administration would never let him anaya rest apodaca said 
we were simply talking about prevailing attitudes in the 
administration apodaca said 
repeated telephone calls to ehrlichmans santa fe home saturday 
reached an answering machine albuquerque fbi spokesman doug belden 
referred questions on the issue to us attorney william lutz who 
denied that anayas remark prompted the federal investigations 
its untrue lutz said late saturday its unfortunate 
that he anaya would attack president reagan in that manner 
reagan spokesman mark weinberg in los angeles said there would 
be no comment from the former president and suggested talking to 
the fbi 
during anayas term lutz conducted an extensive investigation 
into the governors finances anaya at the time accused the 
prosecutor of using a federal grand jury to investigate the 
governors involvement in land transactions in new mexico and 
pennsylvania 
the irs investigated anayas tax liabilities in 1983 and 1984 
according to court documents the fbi investigated the awarding of 
a state fair concession contract after an unsuccessful bidder told 
agents hed heard a payoff had been made to anaya 
anaya said saturday that the various federal agencies that 
launched investigations repeatedly leaked information to the news 
media in their campaign against him and accused news organizations 
of fanning the flames 
anaya acknowledging his administration made many mistakes said 
he believes he was singled out by federal agencies because of 
differences with the rightwing reagan administration over his 
liberal leftwing philosophy 
we had a progressive agenda and that was not going to set very 
well with them he said we had taken on ronald reagan 
personally 
anaya became the states 21st governor behind a wave of 
bipartisan support but his four years in office were plagued by 
controversy and criticism often from the media by the end of his 
administration anayas approval rating in public opinion polls had 
dipped to about 12 percent 
he suffered critical reviews for his good friday 1986 
proclamation that new mexico was a state of sanctuary for central 
american refugees and his thanksgiving eve decision that year to 
commute the death sentences of the states five death row inmates 
anaya who was ineligible for a second consecutive term was 
succeeded by gov garrey carruthers a republican 
anaya has remained active in the democratic party he is 
chairman of the hispanic caucus for the democratic national 
committee and a member of the partys national executive committee 
he indicated when he left office that he would never again be a 
political candidate but said saturday that that could change 
