<TEXT>
buffalos cashpoor bus and subway system 
shut down early sunday after the city transit authority refused to 
consider a county offer to take over the system 
the last bus finished its run at 301 am leaving new york 
states secondlargest city the largest us metropolitan area 
without any public transit system more than 120000 people use 
buffalos system daily 
a city labor leader labeled the conflict a class struggle 
against selfish suburbanites who didnt want to pay for a system 
they dont use 
erie county executive dennis gorski said saturday afternoon hed 
asked a cincinnati management firm to administer the transit system 
for the county if the niagara frontier transportation authority was 
willing to yield control 
but the authority meeting with gorski and city officials 
saturday night refused to take up the offer and voted 72 to shut 
down the system repeating a similar vote take wednesday 
gorski had said a countyrun system would eliminate all but a 
small core of bus and subway routes but would be better than no 
system at all the alternatives are disastrous he told a news 
conference 
you think i want a bus system gorski asked i dont want 
it but ive got to keep it going 
about 80 percent of the transit systems 1043 workers had 
already been laid off by saturday afternoon authority spokesman 
daryl rasuli said 
on wednesday the county legislature rejected a proposed tax on 
public utilities to fund transit after vigorous opposition from 
business leaders the next day the transit agencys board approved 
the shutdown 81 
attempts thursday and friday to put together a bailout plan 
collapsed gorski rejected mayor james griffins proposal to use 
county sales taxes for transit the board turned down gorskis call 
for sweeping service cuts and reorganizing the transit agency 
the utility tax would have raised 9 million for the transit 
system which costs about 55 million a year to run it has been 
squeezed by declining federal subsidies and had only 89000 in the 
bank as of saturday night 
among the first to be affected by a shutdown would be buffalo 
sabres hockey fans about 3000 of the 16000 fans expected to 
attend sunday nights season finale against the quebec nordiques 
would normally have taken the subway to memorial auditorium 
taxi companies said they would be overworked because only 375 
cabs are licensed to pick up people within city limits 
without a transit system more than 12000 public and private 
schoolchildren who normally ride the bus or subway to school would 
be stranded said william goldbach assistant city school 
superintendent for transportation goldbach said it would take 240 
school buses to carry those children but said there simply 
arent enough bus drivers and vehicles available in the area 
some downtown merchants planned to arrange car pools or taxis 
for their employees but others said they were waiting to see what 
happened 
about 110 people attended a noontime rally saturday sponsored by 
the buffalo teachers federation 
union president phil rumore said the shutdown was a class 
struggle against wealthy suburbanites and business interests 
whose lobbying campaign sank the utility proposal 
were talking about people that have saying the havenots 
dont need a public transportation system rumore said 
leonard braun new york area manager for the federal urban mass 
transit administration said he knew of no other transit system 
that had ever been shut down by its own board for lack of funds 
but braun said there was no chance the federal government would 
come to the rescue calling the 1974 decision to provide operating 
subsidies for mass transit a mistake 
</TEXT>
