<DOCNO> AP900401-0017 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the army is speeding up development of a 
weapon to shoot down enemy satellites but has quietly dropped its 
goal of building enough of the hittokill rockets by the 
mid1990s to knock out all soviet military satellites 
the defense department asked congress to nearly triple the 
projects budget for the fiscal year starting oct 1 to 208 
million that would make it one of the fastest growing us weapons 
programs at a time when congress is hailing the end of the cold war 
as reason to scale back defense spending 
the army estimates the total cost of an antisatellite system at 
between 2 billion and 25 billion most of that to be spent over 
the next five years 
the army plans to develop two means of attacking satellites 
with kinetic or nonexplosive warheads fired from 30foot 
missiles based on us territory and with groundbased lasers 
the army has put the kinetic warhead system on a fast 
development track in february it began soliciting bids from 
industry to build between 60 and 75 of the weapons a contractor is 
scheduled to be selected in july and full scale development would 
start in 1992 
the laser program is much further behind 
while the pace of work on kinetic antisatellite or asat 
weaponry is picking up the size of the eventual system has been 
scaled back according to army officials 
brig gen morgan jellett who is in charge of the asat program 
said that until last december the army had planned to buy 300 of 
the weapons or double the number of soviet satellites now 
deployed in december it was decided that 60 to 75 weapons would be 
enough to attack the most crucial soviet space targets he said 
congressional debate on the defense budget so far this year has 
focused mainly on biggercost projects such as the b2 bomber the 
mx intercontinental ballistic missile and other strategic systems 
and on savings from demobilizing troops the antisatellite 
program however is beginning to draw more attention 
im going to do everything i can to scrub it sen dale 
bumpers dark a member of the senate appropriations committee 
said in an interview it just doesnt make any sense 
bumpers said the soviets limited antisatellite capability is 
no threat to us space interests and that the bush administration 
should take up the soviets offer to negotiate a ban on the systems 
before both sides shell out billions to build them 
the groundbased antisatellite program as described by its 
managers in recent interviews at the armys strategic defense 
command in huntsville ala would not violate us arms treaty 
obligations yet critics say it could reignite the superpower arms 
race 
sen john glenn dohio said in a march 7 floor speech that he 
feared the united states could be sparking a superpower asat 
race especially damaging to us space interests particularly 
since the air force this year retired its fleet of sr71 blackbird 
spy planes which are less vulnerable to attack than lowearth 
orbit satellites 
even the army acknowledges that the soviets probably would 
respond to deployment of us antisatellite or asat weapons by 
fielding their own version to knock out us satellites improving 
defenses for their own satellites and by developing a weapon to 
attack the us antisatellite systems 
jellett sought to play down the countermeasures issue 
saying we dont see those being developed anytime soon 
yet an october 1989 strategic defense command document outlining 
a management plan for asat work said that as early as 1996 the 
projected start of deploying a us antisatellite system moscow 
would have the technical and economic means to respond by 
enhancing the effectiveness of their force and degrading the 
effectiveness of the american system were it to be operated 
the 150pound kinetic warheads often called hittokill 
projectiles because they would literally destroy a target by 
ramming it enjoys the advantage over lasers of being effective in 
any weather conditions and of making an easily verified kill 
the advantage of the laser is that it would produce less debris 
in space and could make a covert strike disabling a satellite by 
blinding its electronics system but not causing it to explode 
jellett said a laser asat weapon could be used for example to 
covertly disable the soviet mir space station which us officials 
claim could be used for surveillance and military targeting 
jellett said the mir would be one of the main targets of an asat 
system but for the purpose of disabling it not destroying it 
the army work is not part of the strategic defense initiative 
known as star wars which would put weapons in space to shoot down 
ballistic missiles 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

