decades before mcdonalds flaunted its 
golden arches a roadside diner that looked like a beached tugboat 
lured customers with oldfashioned root beer and a newfangled 
idea a driveup window 
clarence donley boasts his maidrite sandwich shop has the 
worlds first and oldest driveup window although experts on 
commercial architecture say that claim would be hard to prove 
still the 66yearold building is listed on the national 
register of historic places with such prestigious springfield 
monuments as lincolns tomb the statehouse and the executive 
mansion 
in terms of fastfood chains it is one of the oldest existing 
restaurants in the country said michael b jackson an architect 
with the illinois historic preservation agency 
driveup restaurants like maidrite antecedents of todays 
major fastfood chains began popping up across the country in the 
early 1920s 
the springfield building opened in 1924 donley said the shop 
became part of the maidrite chain whose claim to fame is a 
sandwich of crumbled steamed ground beef and onions when the 
chain was founded a couple of years later 
today about 100 maidrites are scattered across the midwest 
but the springfield one is the only one still operating out of its 
original building 
the original red and white woodframed structure was narrow and 
shaped like a tugboat it had three stools at its counter and room 
for at most 13 skinny customers in woodbenched booths 
donley bought the shop 19 years ago and in 1985 expanded the 
store to almost three times its original size 
it hasnt lost its historical significance because of the 
addition jackson said i think they did a good job of 
preserving the original form of the building 
jackson who is also a spokesman for the washington dcbased 
society for commercial archeology said the claim that the 
maidrite driveup window is the oldest is not unreasonable 
but would be difficult to substantiate 
he said the organizations newsletter may carry a notice asking 
if anyone knows of an older driveup window 
donley prides himself on not giving in to the whims of the 
fastfood culture he still serves the same basic menu of maidrite 
loosemeat hamburgers french fries and root beer in a frosty mug 
