the united states is considering bold 
imaginative proposals to deal with controversial nato plans for a 
new shortrange nuclear missile in europe a senior administration 
official said 
the idea of updating the lance missile which would be based on 
west german soil and used to halt a soviet thrust through central 
europe has run into trouble in congress 
it also has encountered fierce public opposition in west germany 
in light of moves toward democracy in poland and hungary and by 
the prospects for german reunification 
a nato meeting last spring in brussels nearly collapsed over the 
issue when us and british officials pressed for the 
modernization of the lance but ran into stiff opposition from west 
german and other alliance members 
in the end the alliance smoothed over the matter by agreeing to 
postpone a decision on deploying the missile until 1992 
but the surge of change in europe and pressure in congress for 
slashing the us military budget is forcing open the debate once 
again 
in his 1991 pentagon budget defense secretary dick cheney has 
asked congress for 1122 million to develop a new shortrange 
missile as a replacement for the aging groundbased lance 
currently deployed throughout europe 
faced with the prospect of a balky congress and another 
intraalliance showdown over the issue at the annual spring session 
of natos nuclear planning group officials on both sides of the 
atlantic are working on alternative ideas said the us official 
who spoke friday on condition of anonymity 
the official declined to elaborate nor would he answer directly 
when asked whether us officials were contemplating dropping the 
idea of moving ahead with the lance modernization 
but he said a host of informal ideas are being studied he 
emphasized that no formal administration decisions have been made 
on the missile issue 
cables are flying all around the official said were 
looking for bold imaginative proposals to present at the npg 
nuclear planning group 
the session is informally scheduled for next month 
the official pointed out that it is an alliance matter that must 
be dealt with within the framework of negotiations inside the nato 
partnership 
we dont have anything hard and fast yet the official said 
but its clear that the alliance isnt sitting on its hands 
he added we know that the world has changed 
in an interview earlier this month with the publication defense 
news gen colin powell the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff 
said he had not discussed alternative lance deployments such as 
basing unassembled missiles in britain 
the lance issue opens a pandoras box of questions since it is 
not the alliances only shortrange nuclear missile 
such missiles have not been included in any superpower arms 
control negotiations but the west germans would like to see them 
introduced into the process 
formally the alliance has said it will not enter into such 
talks until after the eastwest conventional force reduction talks 
are implemented 
the alliances military strategy is based on the concept of 
flexible response the idea that it must have a landbased 
nuclear capability to respond to a soviet assault 
the removal of the intermediaterange nuclear missiles under the 
inf ussoviet missile accord left the shortrange nuclear weapons 
as the major landbased system 
there are 88 lance missile launchers in europe each with a 
range of less than 100 miles the updated version of the weapon 
would be able to reach targets up to 280 miles away 
most of the 88 launchers and their 700 warheads are based on 
west german soil 
but us military officials have warned recently that despite 
the changes that have swept the warsaw pact theyve seen little 
reduction in its stockpile of tactical nuclear weapons 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
a panel of congressional leaders scholars former government 
officials and retired military officers has suggested the 
administrations 1122 million request for the lance program 
would be better spent elsewhere 
in a report sponsored by the johns hopkins foreign policy 
institute the group said the us nuclear guarantee and the 
presence of a substantial number of us troops in europe will 
continue to serve us interests for years to come 
the study put forward to a group of defense writers by sen 
william cohen rmaine and former defense secretary harold brown 
said however that the mission number and structure of 
shortrange nuclear forces should be reviewed prior to the opening 
of talks on these weapons 
in view of us budgetary constraints and west germanys firm 
opposition to deploying new shortrange nucleararmed missiles 
the group concludes that funds requested in the fiscal 1991 budget 
for the lance modernization program would be better spent 
elsewhere a statement by the group said 
</TEXT>
