<TEXT>
east germans are becoming restless with worry 
that they will be plunged into poverty when their nation is unified 
with west germany the countrys outgoing communist premier said in 
an interview published sunday 
hans modrow who stands to lose his job in the coming weeks when 
a new government takes office said west german chancellor helmut 
kohl is backing away from promises to east german voters that their 
money would be worth the same as west german marks 
modrow said kohl was able to influence the outcome of the east 
german elections by promising prosperity to east german voters if 
they elected candidates who favor the chancellors plan for quick 
unification 
inevitably a situation has therefore developed which 
contradicts all that chancellor kohl repeatedly said during the 
election campaign modrow was quoted as saying by the west german 
bild newspaper 
modrow told the paper that east germans are becoming 
increasingly upset that they will be shortchanged by the 
monetary merger he said kohl should bear responisibility for any 
strikes or demonstrations 
some believe the debate over the conversion rate could affect 
the outcome of west germanys general election later this year and 
determine how many more east germans flee their country for the 
west 
east germans reacted with alarm this weekend after the west 
german central bank announced it was proposing an exchange rate of 
two east german marks for one west german mark as part of a plan to 
merge the nations currencies 
following a meeting between the east german christian democrat 
chairman lothar de maiziere and social democrat deputy chief 
markus merkel both men said they rejected the proposed 21 
monetary union rate 
our goal is a money exchange of 11 de maiziere told 
reporters i see no clear or understandable reason to change that 
position 
merkel said the social democrats reject the 21 proposed rate as 
totally unacceptable 
meanwhile the head of east germanys labor union federation 
helga mausch told the official news agency adn that the 
organization was urging its 86 million members to fight for 
their rights and demonstrate next week against the proposed 
exchange rate 
east germans who have amassed large savings because of a 
shortage of consumer goods under the communists were hoping for a 
11 conversion based on election campaign speeches made by kohl 
and other conservatives 
kohl said saturday he never promised an equal exchange of east 
german marks for west german marks but modrow said kohl did 
he promised it again and again bild quoted modrow as 
saying the voters clearly saw it that way the outcome of the 
election was as a result of those promises 
east germans voting in their first free elections on march 18 
overwhelmingly chose a christian democratled conservative 
alliance that kohl helped organized 
kohl made regular trips to the east to campaign for the 
coalition 
the christian democrats continued to negotiate sunday with the 
secondplace finisher in the election the leftleaning social 
democrats on forming a coalition that would dominate east 
germanys new 400member parliament 
modrow leads the overhauled communist party that embraced a form 
of democratic socialism after the old stalinist regime was 
overthrown during last years mass demonstrations 
the communists finished a distant third in the elections the 
new parliament is expected to convene for the first time this week 
under the exchange rate established by the former communist 
regime three east german marks bought one west german mark the 
east german mark is nonconvertible however and has virtually no 
value in western markets 
karl otto poehl the chairman of west germanys bundesbank said 
saturday the state banks plan for a 21 conversion actually raises 
the value of the east german mark small savings accounts of up to 
2000 marks 1175 still would be exchanged at a 11 rate poehl 
said 
kohls government facing elections in december is trying to 
walk a fine line between living up to election promises to east 
german voters without placing too great an economic burden on west 
german voters 
east germanys collapsing economy and the nearly 500000 east 
germans who fled to the west since january 1989 were main factors 
in the revolt that ousted the old communist regime 
some officials including ulf fink of kohls christian 
democratic union have predicted that anything less than a 11 
conversion could cause a new exodus of east germans to the west 
another exodus would be more costly than a general 11 rate 
for all savings fink was quoted by the neue osnabreucker zeitung 
as saying 
west german financial experts say it will cost hundreds of 
billions of marks to improve obsolete industries and repair roads 
and communications in east germany 
much of that burden is expected to affect the wealthy west 
german economy possibly resulting in rising inflation a decline 
in the value of the powerful west mark and perhaps new taxes 
proponents of a 11 conversion say it is necessary to allow east 
german workers and elderly people living off savings accounts to 
maintain adequate living standards in a unified germany 
east germans currently depend on heavy government subsidies for 
housing food and employment the subsidies will be quickly phased 
out in the new freemarket economy when unification comes 
</TEXT>
