<TEXT>
efforts to notify the sex partners of 
syphilis patients is unlikely to control the spread of the disease 
because many of those infected have multiple anonymous partners 
according to a study released sunday 
the results reported in mondays issue of the annals of 
internal medicine suggest that efforts to fight aids by notifying 
patients partners is likely to fail too said an accompanying 
editorial in the journal 
the 1988 study conducted by oregon health officials and the 
us centers for disease control focused on 146 syphilisinfected 
adults treated over four months overall the patients were able to 
identify an average of just one in five of their sexual partners 
according to the report 
twentyeight percent of the patients reported exchanging sex for 
drugs or money and that group accounted for 72 percent of the 
unlocatable sexual partners 
a strategy of controlling syphilis which relies solely or 
mostly on partner notification is doomed to failure because it is 
at most only 20 percent effective said one of the studys 
authors dr david fleming of the oregon health division 
oregon state law requires that syphilis cases be reported to 
county and state health officials 
each patient had an average of five sex partners during the 
study period whom they could not identify sufficiently for partner 
notification the study found 
in contrast a comparison group of 164 oregon adults with 
gonorrhea which is also sexually transmitted reported an average 
of less than one anonymous sex partner 
syphilis a chronic sexually transmitted disease is at its 
highest national rate in 40 years infecting about 16 people out of 
every 100000 in 1988 39000 cases were reported according to 
the cdc 
because of syphilis long infectious period and the likelihood 
that some patients engage in prostitution or drug use the 
researchers said partner notification wont control its spread 
because aids is prevalent among those with multiple sex partners 
and intravenous drug users partner notification for those patients 
will be fraught with the same problems fleming said 
instead contact tracing should be supplemented by vigorous and 
aggressive voluntary screening and educational programs the 
researchers said 
despite a medical treatment for syphilis the resurgence of 
this disease in the heterosexual population may be an alarming 
prelude to an epidemic of aids in the same population the 
researchers wrote 
the editorialist allan brandt of harvard medical school said 
that despite calls for mandatory contact tracing of aids patients 
the oregon study points out the great uncertainty that partner 
notification effectively serves the goals of public health and 
welfare 
