a 30milelong fuel slick left a town of about 
15000 people without normal water sunday and threatened water 
supplies in pittsburgh and dozens of other cities dependent on the 
allegheny and ohio rivers authorities said 
the slick moving sluggishly down the allegheny northwest of 
pittsburgh resulted from a landslide that cracked a pipeline 
friday the pipeline released a mixture of gasoline kerosene and 
lesser amounts of other fuels into a tributary creek at freeport 
about 35 miles northeast of pittsburgh 
